 abstract = {Electrocortical polyspiking has been reported in guinea pigs, tottering mice, and several strains of laboratory rats. Some investigators have interpreted the polyspiking activity (PSA) to be epileptic in nature, specifically analogous to human petit mal spike-wave discharges; others have assumed PSA to be the rodent equivalent of human mu and feline sensorimotor rhythms. This article provides additional data on PSA in rats, consistent with previous reports that it is associated with behavioral immobility, occurs spontaneously, is bilaterally {\dots}},
